article1 = Article.create(
  content: "AdvertisementTKTKSupported byTKTKThe podcast premiered during the pandemic and brought friends â€” and the friends you wish you had â€” together.TKTKBy Nathan Taylor PembertonTKTKDuring the confusing early days of the pandemic in spring 2020, there were a number of attempts at forging human connection, some more regrettable than others: things like the Houseparty app, socially distanced comedy specials, nightly essential worker celebrations, not to mention the social hegemon, Zoom.TKTKAnd, of course, there were pandemic podcasts, which covered everything from the scariness of daily news to celebrations of minor tasks to quarantine-themed close reads of the â€œTwilightâ€ series. More than a year later, many such shows have gone dark, as the world eagerly moves on.TKTKOne exception to the boom and bust of the quarantine content cycle is the podcast â€œHow Long Gone.â€ The show, which premiered in March 2020, was born out of a Twitter joke between Chris Black and Jason Stewart. Longtime friends, they began posting, three times a week, hourlong FaceTime calls with each other and a grab bag of famous-ish friends and acquaintances in media, fashion, music and film. Early guests included the actress Tavi Gevinson, the writer Cat Marnell, the singer Phoebe Bridgers and the playwright and screenwriter Jeremy O. Harris.TKTKNow, more than 200 episodes later, â€œHow Long Goneâ€ has become a staple for many media insiders, culture makers, very online people and even your average â€œbroâ€ â€” making it a clubhouse for the chattering classes.TKTKIts mix of Twitter-centric water cooler talk, free-form bull session, and a deluge of takes â€œsprayedâ€ by its hosts has pushed the podcast to outgrow its origin story. Within months of their first episode, the show reached monthly listener figures in the six digits, they cracked the top 50 on Appleâ€™s comedy charts and were asked to host a new podcast for Spotify: â€œHow Long Gone Radio.â€TKTKItâ€™s even earned them a special kind of celebrity.TKTKâ€œPeople at Erewhon are starting to recognize us,â€ said Mr. Black, 39, of the trendy grocery store in Los Angeles, where he and Mr. Stewart live.TKTKâ€œHow Long Goneâ€ billed itself as a â€œbicoastal elite podcast from old friendsâ€ in its inaugural episode. There is, to be sure, some truth to the bicoastal elite thing. Mr. Black works as a consultant for fashion brands like Thom Browne and writes for culture magazines; he keeps an apartment in New York City, where he used to live. And Mr. Stewart, 41, is a prolific podcaster on his own, having first made his name as a party D.J. with Steve Aokiâ€™s Dim Mak crew in the early 2000s.TKTKDuring one recent episode featuring A.J. Daulerio, a former editor of Gawker and Deadspin, the pair opened the show by covering a spree of trending topics: a viral milk story published on Grub Street, milk crate challenges and the appearance of one of Mr. Blackâ€™s tweets (about the milk story) in a New York Post story.TKTKâ€œThe milk story was brilliant because everyone has an opinion on it,â€ Mr. Black said during the episode. â€œAnd itâ€™s absolutely meaningless.â€TKTKOnce the giggling and verbal horseplay subsided, they yielded the floor to Mr. Daulerio, who talked about the drug abuse that marked his reign at Gawker and about his new Substack, which focuses on subjects like substance abuse and recovery. (Mr. Black sometimes uses the podcast to speak openly about his past struggles with drug abuse and his current sobriety.)TKTKTheir conversation soon settled into a broader discussion of New York publishing, their preferred newsletter subscriptions and media consumption habits. Mr. Black is fond of print magazines and Airmail, Graydon Carterâ€™s once-a-week email newsletter. Mr. Stewart is less interested in print media and prefers to listen to articles on the Pocket app.TKTKâ€œThis is my favorite New York media podcast,â€ Mr. Daulerio said at one point. He added with some wonder: â€œYou guys can say â€˜fireâ€™ and â€˜broâ€™ so effortlessly.â€TKTKAttributing the showâ€™s steady success to its insider-baseball-like chats or the hostsâ€™ exaggerated takes on just about everything under the sun would miss the point. Thereâ€™s likely a more simple explanation: the appeal of two grown men engaging in nontoxic masculinity.TKTKâ€œItâ€™s rare and special and eternally fun to listen to people who are really close, who can point out each otherâ€™s flaws in a healthy and positive way,â€ Mr. Stewart said, on a recent Zoom call with Mr. Black. â€œNegativity is not entertaining to us.â€TKTKMr. Black added: â€œJust in a lighthearted, fun way. I like punching up.â€TKTKThey are, of course, far from the first pair of friends to turn genuine rapport into digestible content. Last November, Vogue cited â€œHow Long Goneâ€ as proof of the rise of the â€œbro-cast,â€ but noted that the format had been popularized quite successfully by women-led shows like â€œCall Your Girlfriend,â€ hosted by two â€œlong-distance besties,â€ long before the quarantine era.TKTKAnother podcast built around a close personal rapport is â€œRed Scare,â€ hosted by Anna Khachiyan and Dasha Nekrasova. The podcastâ€™s focus is political and generally takes up a trolling critique of liberal feminism in all its forms, but Ms. Nekrasova attributes a large degree of the showâ€™s success to the friendship that is centered in each episode. She came on â€œHow Long Goneâ€ last November after receiving an Instagram message from Mr. Black, whom she knew little about.TKTKAnd with so many podcasts operating like mere â€œfriendship simulators,â€ as Ms. Nekrasova calls them, she was surprised by the ease with which Mr. Black and Mr. Stewart integrated her into their pop culture musings. â€œItâ€™s clear what they have is real,â€ she said. â€œMost podcasts take a while to develop a friendship, especially when itâ€™s front and center to the show. But itâ€™s easy for them. Theyâ€™re good at keeping that ball in the air.â€TKTKAt a ceaseless pace, they have leveraged their micro-celebrity to pursue their own low-stakes interests. Multiple runs of hats, tote bags and a $40 â€œPerformanceâ€ Nalgene bottle â€” mostly designed by Mr. Stewart â€” have sold out, they said. They have released their own brand of â€œsnapchilledâ€ canned coffee, named Mudd, and for a short while, Angelenos could start their day with â€œthe Goner,â€ a vegan breakfast sandwich made in collaboration with local chain Burgerlords.TKTKStill, they havenâ€™t put their podcast behind a paywall, opting for more aesthetically aligned sponsorships with companies like the podcasting platform Anchor.FM. â€œWe want as many people to hear this podcast as possible, and if you put a paywall up thatâ€™s not going to happen,â€ Mr. Black said.TKTKâ€œPeople donâ€™t really want to support us that much,â€ Mr. Stewart added, dryly.TKTKNor have they fully abandoned their day jobs. Mr. Stewart consults for other podcasts, while Mr. Black works with fashion clients. With audiences hyper-attuned to all things that could be deemed performative, and listeners and viewers ever more cynical to the dynamics of self-branding, Mr. Black and Mr. Stewart seem to have dialed into the right frequency of realness.TKTKâ€œThere are loads of podcasts that are intelligent and well researched, but they donâ€™t necessarily have people I wish I was hanging out with,â€ said Raven Smith, a columnist for Vogue, who has been a guest on the show.TKTKIt was through a Thom Browne project that Mr. Harris, the writer, first met Mr. Black. The two quickly hit it off and Mr. Harris was invited onto the podcast, becoming one of its earliest guests.TKTKâ€œThereâ€™s a casual intellect that moves past a lot of the performance that one sees in podcasts,â€ Mr. Harris said of the showâ€™s hosts. â€œThey have an overwhelming sense of curiosity in who you are and the world youâ€™re a part of. And thatâ€™s what sets them apart. They are classic radio hosts.â€TKTKMr. Black and Mr. Stewart have yet to record an episode in the same room. However, this fall, they are planning to take the show into the real world after being signed by High Road Touring, a talent booking agency. â€œGoners,â€ as the showâ€™s fans are referred to, will be able to see a â€œDavid Letterman-styleâ€ live show during an 11-city tour across the country. An Oct. 23 appearance at the Bowery Ballroom in New York is sold out.TKTKThe podcast has a record deal now, too, with the independent label Jagjaguar, home to Bon Iver, Angel Olsen and other musicians. Jagjaguar will release the debut â€œHow Long Goneâ€ album as a part of its 25th anniversary celebration.TKTKBoth hosts came of age toiling in the music industry â€” Mr. Black used to manage the pop punk band Cartel in the early 2000s â€” so their record deal fits squarely with their history.TKTKAnd more broadly, it also may indicate that a successful podcast, in a cultural moment marked by digital novelty, is a quick path to social cachet.TKTKâ€œThrough the pod weâ€™ve been able to clearly see how to accomplish a lot of the dreams and goals in our lives,â€ Mr. Stewart said. â€œWeâ€™ve been able to pull from all the worlds weâ€™ve been a part of and inject it into this experiment that weâ€™re doing. Every little thing can be done the way you want to do it.â€TKTKMuch like their music industry debut, which, Mr. Black noted, will be released as a double compact disc.TKTKâ€œItâ€™s just a fun thing to do,â€ he said. â€œTapes are corny. Vinyl is corny. CDs are cool.â€TKTKAdvertisementTKTK",
  image_url: "https://static01.nyt.com/images/2021/09/23/fashion/23howlonggone1/merlin_179470536_29412ffe-86a6-4a95-83b4-f5b79dee1997-articleLarge.jpg?quality=75&auto=webp&disable=upscale",
  is_read: false,
  link: "https://www.nytimes.com/2021/09/22/style/how-long-gone-podcast.html",
  title: "â€˜How Long Goneâ€™ Is in It for the Long Haul",
  user_id: demo.id
